<h3>Newton=E2=80=93Raphson method<sup id=3D"fnref1:1"><a href=3D"https://pl=
anetcalc.com/7748/#fn:1" class=3D"footnote-ref">1</a></sup></h3>
<p>In numerical analysis, Newton's method (also known as the Newton=E2=80=
=93Raphson method), named after Isaac Newton and Joseph Raphson, is a metho=
d for finding successively better approximations to the roots (or zeroes) o=
f a real-valued function.</p>
<p>The method starts with a function f defined over the real numbers x, the=
 function's derivative f=E2=80=89=E2=80=B2, and an initial guess x0 for a r=
oot of the function f. If the function satisfies the assumptions made in th=
e derivation of the formula and the initial guess is close, then a better a=
pproximation x1 is <img src=3D"https://planetcalc.com/cgi-bin/mimetex.cgi?x=
_%7B1%7D%3Dx_%7B0%7D-%7B%5Cfrac%20%7Bf%28x_%7B0%7D%29%7D%7Bf%27%28x_%7B0%7D=
%29%7D%7D" alt=3D"x_{1}=3Dx_{0}-{\frac {f(x_{0})}{f'(x_{0})}}" class=3D"pc-=
math"></p>
<p>Geometrically, (x1, 0) is the intersection of the x-axis and the tangent=
 of the graph of f at (x0, f(x0)).</p>
<p>The process is repeated as <img src=3D"https://planetcalc.com/cgi-bin/mi=
metex.cgi?x_%7Bn%2B1%7D%3Dx_%7Bn%7D-%7B%5Cfrac%20%7Bf%28x_%7Bn%7D%29%7D%7Bf=
%27%28x_%7Bn%7D%29%7D%7D" alt=3D"x_{n+1}=3Dx_{n}-{\frac {f(x_{n})}{f'(x_{n}=
)}}" class=3D"pc-math">, until a sufficiently accurate value is reached.</p=
>
<p></p><div style=3D"text-align:center"><figure><img class=3D"je" src=3D"ht=
tps://planetcalc.com/users/2/1519890919.gif" alt=3D"Animation of Newton's m=
ethod by Ralf Pfeifer (https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:NewtonIterat=
ion_Ani.gif)" title=3D"Animation of Newton's method by Ralf Pfeifer (https:=
//commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:NewtonIteration_Ani.gif)"><figcaption>Ani=
mation of Newton's method by Ralf Pfeifer (https://commons.wikimedia.org/wi=
ki/File:NewtonIteration_Ani.gif)</figcaption></figure></div><p></p>
<p>The idea of the method is as follows: one starts with an initial guess w=
hich is reasonably close to the true root, then the function is approximate=
d by its tangent line (which can be computed using the tools of calculus), =
and one computes the x-intercept of this tangent line (which is easily done=
 with elementary algebra). This x-intercept will typically be a better appr=
oximation to the function's root than the original guess, and the method ca=
n be iterated.</p>
<p>Newton's method is an extremely powerful technique=E2=80=94in general th=
e convergence is quadratic: as the method converges on the root, the differ=
ence between the root and the approximation is squared (the number of accur=
ate digits roughly doubles) at each step. However, there are some difficult=
ies with the method: difficulty in calculating derivative of a function, fa=
ilure of the method to converge to the root, if the assumptions made in the=
 proof of quadratic convergence of Newton's method are not met, slow conver=
gence for roots of multiplicity greater than 1</p>
